Parameters of disease transmission models including contact rate and infection rate are interconnected and their influences are complementary. The agent-based disease transmission models (including disease spreading models and agent-based models) are highly non-convex, so a reliable mathematical model between the parameters (called dependent factors) and their effects (called responses of interest) are not available. We use a response surface methodology (RSM) to calibrate the disease transmission model. RSM consists of a set of mathematical and statistical techniques used to develop, improve and optimise processes in which a response of interest is influenced by several factors, with the eventual objective of optimising the response (Box and Draper, 2007). Therefore, RSM quantifies the functional relationship between a response of interest, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
